               20
percent during this period, from <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">1,014 to 1,216</NUMEX>.

            <NUMEX TYPE="ORDINAL">Second</NUMEX>, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Besharov</ENAMEX> and Dembosky
misrepresented the NIS methodology for classifying the severity of injury or
harm. (We wish we could ascribe this to misunderstanding, but we clarified this
issue for them before their article's <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">publication</ENAMEX> and they published their
misinformation anyway.) In fact, the classification of a <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">child</ENAMEX> as seriously
injured/harmed is relatively objective in that it does not rely on a blanket
judgment by a respondent. The criteria for defining serious harm or injury are
standardized; they are applied to the described injury itself, not to the
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">respondent</ENAMEX>'s judgment about that injury; and they have been consistent across
the <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">three</NUMEX> incidence studies. So the recent quadrupling of the number of
seriously injured <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">children</ENAMEX> cannot be ascribed to some vague form of
"definitional creep."

